<p><b>Samuel Dashiell Hammett</b> (May 27, 1894—January 10, 1961) was an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> author of <a href="/wiki/Hardboiled" title="Hardboiled">hardboiled</a> <a href="/wiki/Detective_fiction" title="Detective fiction">detective</a> novels and <a href="/wiki/Short_stories" title="Short stories" class="mw-redirect">short stories</a>. Among the enduring characters he created are <a href="/wiki/Sam_Spade" title="Sam Spade">Sam Spade</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/The_Maltese_Falcon" title="The Maltese Falcon" class="mw-redirect">The Maltese Falcon</a></i>), <a href="/wiki/Nick_and_Nora_Charles" title="Nick and Nora Charles">Nick and Nora Charles</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/The_Thin_Man" title="The Thin Man">The Thin Man</a></i>), and <a href="/wiki/The_Continental_Op" title="The Continental Op">the Continental Op</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Red_Harvest" title="Red Harvest">Red Harvest</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Dain_Curse" title="The Dain Curse">The Dain Curse</a></i>). In addition to the significant influence his novels and stories had on film, Hammett "is now widely regarded as one of the finest mystery writers of all time"<sup id="cite_ref-shadow0_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-shadow0-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> and was called, in his obituary in <i><a href="/wiki/The_New_York_Times" title="The New York Times">The New York Times</a></i>, "the dean of the... 'hard-boiled' school of detective fiction".<sup id="cite_ref-hardboiled0_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hardboiled0-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
